00:38:03.420 --> 00:38:06.190
director friend of
mine has just--

00:38:06.190 --> 00:38:09.190
on my Gmail, I just discovered
a message from him, saying

00:38:09.190 --> 00:38:10.440
that I'd be very much
interested.

00:38:15.940 --> 00:38:16.900
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:38:16.900 --> 00:38:19.440
Just curious in terms
of how you would

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:21.080
monetize what you write.

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:23.033
Once you're on your second book,
your third book, you've

00:38:23.033 --> 00:38:25.340
already built up a brand, so
you know, and you have an

00:38:25.340 --> 00:38:26.730
agent, and it's easier
to negotiate.

00:38:26.730 --> 00:38:29.070
But the very first time you
actually write something, how

00:38:29.070 --> 00:38:32.870
do you know once a publisher
says yes, this is a good work,

00:38:32.870 --> 00:38:33.520
I'd like to publish it.

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:35.510
How do you know if you're
getting what it's worth?

00:38:35.510 --> 00:38:37.460
VIKAS SWARUP: That's a very,
very important question.

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:40.350
How do you monetize, because
it's the same question that an

00:38:40.350 --> 00:38:41.840
artist would have to--

00:38:41.840 --> 00:38:44.010
a first-time artist,
he paints a canvas.

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:45.880
Now what price does he charge?

00:38:45.880 --> 00:38:49.480
So there, I think various
factors operate.

00:38:49.480 --> 00:38:52.790
I had an agent, and he was able
to send the manuscript to

00:38:52.790 --> 00:38:54.520
eight or ten different
publishers.

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:57.450
And then depending on the
feedback from the publishers,

00:38:57.450 --> 00:39:01.330
I think there's an instinctive
feel to a book the moment it

00:39:01.330 --> 00:39:02.500
lands at a publisher's place.

00:39:02.500 --> 00:39:05.670
They think of it either as a
small book, or a medium book,

00:39:05.670 --> 00:39:06.750
or a big book.

00:39:06.750 --> 00:39:10.120
And the size of the advance is
commensurate with the placing

00:39:10.120 --> 00:39:11.170
of their book.

00:39:11.170 --> 00:39:14.320
And if they feel that it's a big
book, then sometimes you

00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:16.570
go into an auction situation
where two publishers are

00:39:16.570 --> 00:39:19.040
competing with each other in
order to get the rights.

00:39:19.040 --> 00:39:22.660
But for me, to be very honest,
the important thing was not

00:39:22.660 --> 00:39:24.910
the monetary factor, that how
much will I get for it.

00:39:24.910 --> 00:39:28.650
The important thing was how much
will the publisher invest

00:39:28.650 --> 00:39:31.160
in terms of promoting the
book, in terms of

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:31.910
publicizing the book.

00:39:31.910 --> 00:39:34.600
Because these days, the
old saying, any

00:39:34.600 --> 00:39:35.860
fool can write a book.

00:39:35.860 --> 00:39:37.220
It takes a genius to sell one.

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:44.660
Yes.

00:39:44.660 --> 00:39:46.660
AUDIENCE: Hi, Vikas.

00:39:46.660 --> 00:39:49.328
I have two questions at once.

00:39:49.328 --> 00:39:51.064
I'm from the Mumbai office.

00:39:51.064 --> 00:39:54.920
What I wanted to know is when
you start writing a book, do

00:39:54.920 --> 00:39:57.111
you always envision
the ending?

00:39:57.111 --> 00:39:59.070
Do you know where you
want to get to?

00:39:59.070 --> 00:40:01.666
And in that way, do you sort of
walk your way towards the

00:40:01.666 --> 00:40:04.601
ending, or do you plan it out
very carefully and have road

00:40:04.601 --> 00:40:06.220
maps toward it?

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:08.670
VIKAS SWARUP: Well, I always
start with the ending.

00:40:08.670 --> 00:40:12.750
Now I have a perfected my
formula for writing the kind

00:40:12.750 --> 00:40:14.970
of books I write, which I
call social thrillers.

00:40:14.970 --> 00:40:16.940
It's the hook, line,
and sinker.

00:40:16.940 --> 00:40:20.320
So first is you have to have a
hook, a hook that can entice

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:21.330
the reader in.

00:40:21.330 --> 00:40:24.080
So in the first book, the hook
was how does he answer those

00:40:24.080 --> 00:40:26.900
questions, the 12 or 13
questions that he's asked.

00:40:26.900 --> 00:40:29.100
In the second book, it was the
six suspects, which one of

00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:30.090
them is the murderer?

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:32.140
And in the current book,
it's the seven tests.

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:33.540
Will Sapna pass those
seven tests?

00:40:33.540 --> 00:40:34.200
Will she fail?

00:40:34.200 --> 00:40:35.530
Are the seven tests for real?

00:40:35.530 --> 00:40:36.370
Are they not for real?

00:40:36.370 --> 00:40:37.490
So that's the first thing--

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:40.410
create a hook which can entice
the reader into the book.

00:40:40.410 --> 00:40:42.060
The second is the line.

00:40:42.060 --> 00:40:45.330
Have a dramatic narrative, a
narrative in which there are

00:40:45.330 --> 00:40:48.930
lots of twists and turns, things
keep on happening to

00:40:48.930 --> 00:40:50.190
keep the reader engaged.

00:40:50.190 --> 00:40:52.650
And sinker in the sense
that emotional

00:40:52.650 --> 00:40:53.850
attachment to the character.

00:40:53.850 --> 00:40:56.010
If that character sinks,
your heart sinks,

00:40:56.010 --> 00:40:57.200
that kind of a thing.

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:59.910
So that is how I like
to frame my books.

00:40:59.910 --> 00:41:02.900
But for me, the ending comes
first because I want to give a

00:41:02.900 --> 00:41:04.470
surprise at the end
to the reader.

00:41:04.470 --> 00:41:07.630
And for that, you have to work
backwards from the ending and

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:11.420
then sort of put in the other
milestones in place.

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:12.050
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:12.050 --> 00:41:14.710
First of all, I wanted to
confess, being a big quizzer

00:41:14.710 --> 00:41:18.880
myself, I really enjoyed "Q &amp;
A." And that actually inspired

00:41:18.880 --> 00:41:21.180
me to keep on quizzing.

00:41:21.180 --> 00:41:22.605
So I just wanted to
give that to you.

00:41:22.605 --> 00:41:26.290
My question is you obviously
travel a lot.

00:41:26.290 --> 00:41:29.420
And I'm sure there are some
instances where you come

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:31.290
across some situations that you
say, this would probably

00:41:31.290 --> 00:41:34.230
make an interesting situation
in my book.

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:35.885
So has your travels
kind of inspired

00:41:35.885 --> 00:41:38.940
you to write something?

00:41:38.940 --> 00:41:41.930
And are you planning on writing
some nonfiction also?

00:41:41.930 --> 00:41:43.860
I mean, you've stuck
with fiction.

00:41:43.860 --> 00:41:45.520
Any plans of writing
nonfiction?

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:47.130
VIKAS SWARUP: I mean, no writer
writes in a vacuum.

00:41:47.130 --> 00:41:49.330
Even though I write about India,
but I write about India

00:41:49.330 --> 00:41:51.950
living in South Africa
or Japan where

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:53.400
I'm currently residing.

00:41:53.400 --> 00:41:56.250
The fact that you are living
there means that you are

00:41:56.250 --> 00:41:57.840
having some experiences there.

00:41:57.840 --> 00:42:00.270
You are meeting people, you're
having conversations.

00:42:00.270 --> 00:42:03.990
And subconsciously, some of
those experiences, some of

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:06.350
those conversations return to
your writing, even though it

00:42:06.350 --> 00:42:08.440
may not be immediately
obvious.

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:11.450
So certainly the fact that I'm
living in Japan and that I'm

00:42:11.450 --> 00:42:13.360
interacting with people
there has had an

00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:14.420
impact on my writing.

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:17.430
But I still feel most connected
with India.

00:42:17.430 --> 00:42:20.120
And even though I live thousands
of kilometers away

00:42:20.120 --> 00:42:24.900
from India, because of 21st
century technology, I can

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:27.410
watch events happening in India
real time sitting in

00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:29.690
Japan as you would
sitting here.

00:42:29.690 --> 00:42:32.590
So I do not feel that I'm
at a remove from India.

00:42:32.590 --> 00:42:34.680
In fact, sometimes distance
gives you a

00:42:34.680 --> 00:42:36.280
better perspective also.

00:42:36.280 --> 00:42:37.240
So that is there.

00:42:37.240 --> 00:42:42.120
But having said that, I still
want to create works based on

00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:47.420
my invented landscape and
invented characters.

00:42:47.420 --> 00:42:51.000
The diplomatic trivia of my
day job could be of great

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:54.310
interest, but I feel that what
I create in my books--

00:42:54.310 --> 00:42:57.100
murder and mayhem and all kinds
of things happening--

00:42:57.100 --> 00:42:59.700
would still be of greater
interest.

00:42:59.700 --> 00:43:01.920
So as of now, I would like
to stick to fiction.

00:43:01.920 --> 00:43:03.910
And what I love about fiction
is that there are no

00:43:03.910 --> 00:43:04.900
boundaries.

00:43:04.900 --> 00:43:07.920
A fiction writer creates
a world in which

00:43:07.920 --> 00:43:09.250
he frames the rules.

00:43:09.250 --> 00:43:10.980
The laws of physics
don't operate.

00:43:10.980 --> 00:43:12.400
The laws of the writer
operate.

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:16.116
And that's the great thing
I like about future.

00:43:16.116 --> 00:43:17.520
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:18.009
VIKAS SWARUP: Yes.

00:43:18.009 --> 00:43:20.454
AUDIENCE: Have ever encountered
what they call as

00:43:20.454 --> 00:43:24.366
"writer's block" and then know
how to move forward and how

00:43:24.366 --> 00:43:26.330
would you face it?

00:43:26.330 --> 00:43:28.430
VIKAS SWARUP: I don't have
writer's block, but I've had

00:43:28.430 --> 00:43:29.490
writer's cramp.

00:43:29.490 --> 00:43:32.930
My right hand starts cramping
if I hold the

00:43:32.930 --> 00:43:34.125
pen for very long.

00:43:34.125 --> 00:43:36.200
Surprisingly, the only time it
works brilliantly is when I'm

00:43:36.200 --> 00:43:36.980
signing books.

00:43:36.980 --> 00:43:39.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:39.610 --> 00:43:41.510
VIKAS SWARUP: But otherwise,
I've had banks returning my

00:43:41.510 --> 00:43:43.800
checks saying this signature
does not match the one which

00:43:43.800 --> 00:43:45.080
we have on record and
things like that.

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:47.400
No, I've been a lucky writer in
the sense that I've never

00:43:47.400 --> 00:43:48.480
had writer's block.

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:50.600
Or at least I've never had
writers block for an extended

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:51.520
period of time.

00:43:51.520 --> 00:43:54.200
Certainly, sometimes you sit
in front of the computer

00:43:54.200 --> 00:43:56.990
screen and you wonder how are
you going to fill that screen

00:43:56.990 --> 00:43:58.950
with words, and nothing
is happening.

00:43:58.950 --> 00:44:01.480
But those occasions
are very rare.

00:44:01.480 --> 00:44:03.880
Normally, my mind is bubbling
with too many ideas, and I

00:44:03.880 --> 00:44:05.250
have to decide which
ones to choose and

00:44:05.250 --> 00:44:06.410
which ones to ignore.

00:44:06.410 --> 00:44:07.660
I think that is important.

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:11.300
At the same time, writing
is a difficult process.

00:44:11.300 --> 00:44:14.160
Dorothy Parker was once asked,
do you love writing?

00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:15.370
And she gave a classic reply.

00:44:15.370 --> 00:44:16.770
She said I hate writing.

00:44:16.770 --> 00:44:19.870
I love having written.

00:44:19.870 --> 00:44:25.320
So when you write, actually,
it's tough work.

00:44:25.320 --> 00:44:28.180
But only afterwards when you
read what you have written and

00:44:28.180 --> 00:44:32.568
then you enjoy that, then you
have a sense of satisfaction.

00:44:32.568 --> 00:44:34.924
AUDIENCE: My question is, are
there any authors you consider

00:44:34.924 --> 00:44:36.852
has your own model of
doing this process?

00:44:36.852 --> 00:44:39.021
And what are your most favorite
books that you've

00:44:39.021 --> 00:44:39.750
read lately?

00:44:39.750 --> 00:44:41.610
VIKAS SWARUP: No, I have
read many authors.

00:44:41.610 --> 00:44:45.010
I had the big advantage,
unlike all you here, of

00:44:45.010 --> 00:44:47.660
growing up in an era where
there was no internet.

00:44:47.660 --> 00:44:49.280
There was no cable television.

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:51.660
There was no television even,
forget cable television.

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:54.560
So the only pastime I had
was reading books.

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:56.770
And I read each and every book
that I could lay my hands

00:44:56.770 --> 00:45:00.115
upon, whether it was Franz
Kafka, Albert Camus, Alistair

00:45:00.115 --> 00:45:03.380
MacLean, Agatha Christie, Earl
Stanley Gardner, you name it.

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:05.160
Any and every book that
I could lay my

00:45:05.160 --> 00:45:06.440
hands upon, I read.

00:45:06.440 --> 00:45:10.060
And I think it was that reading
which I did so many--

00:45:10.060 --> 00:45:12.710
if I wrote this book in two
months, it's because of the 25

00:45:12.710 --> 00:45:15.340
years of reading I did
prior to writing.

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:17.890
So all of those writers I think
shaped me as a writer in

00:45:17.890 --> 00:45:20.990
the sense they allowed me to
discriminate between what is

00:45:20.990 --> 00:45:22.880
good writing and what
is bad writing.

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:26.200
But having said that, you
cannot really adopt the

00:45:26.200 --> 00:45:27.800
writing style of any
other writer.

00:45:27.800 --> 00:45:29.210
You have to find
your own voice.

00:45:29.210 --> 00:45:30.390
You have to find
your own style.

00:45:30.390 --> 00:45:31.900
You have to find
your own idiom.

00:45:31.900 --> 00:45:35.920
And that's what I tried to do in
"Q &amp; A," find the voice of

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:37.090
Ram Mohammed Thomas.

00:45:37.090 --> 00:45:38.570
And once I had those words--

00:45:38.570 --> 00:45:41.150
"I have been arrested for
winning a quiz show"--

00:45:41.150 --> 00:45:43.690
I knew I had the voice of
Ram Mohammed Thomas.

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:47.420
Among the current crop of
writers, I greatly admire J.M.

00:45:47.420 --> 00:45:49.040
Coetzee, the South
African writer.

00:45:49.040 --> 00:45:51.200
I thought "Disgrace" was
an absolute classic.

00:45:51.200 --> 00:45:52.890
I also like Paul Auster.

00:45:52.890 --> 00:45:54.370
I like Haruki Murakami.

00:45:54.370 --> 00:45:56.800
So these are some of the writers
whose writing style I

00:45:56.800 --> 00:45:59.100
like, but some of them
don't believe in a

00:45:59.100 --> 00:46:00.740
resolution at all.

00:46:00.740 --> 00:46:02.970
For me, resolution is
very important.

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:05.950
If a reader has invested time
and money in my book, then I

00:46:05.950 --> 00:46:07.750
don't want the reader to go
puzzling into the night--

00:46:07.750 --> 00:46:08.560
what happened?

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:10.180
Did he die?

00:46:10.180 --> 00:46:12.000
Did he get the money?

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:12.980
Did they get married?

00:46:12.980 --> 00:46:14.900
What happened?

00:46:14.900 --> 00:46:17.460
For me, resolution
is important.

00:46:17.460 --> 00:46:18.710
Yes.

00:46:21.760 --> 00:46:25.240
AUDIENCE: Now that two of your
books are adapted into films,

00:46:25.240 --> 00:46:28.850
how challenging is it
not to think you're

00:46:28.850 --> 00:46:30.110
writing for a film?

00:46:30.110 --> 00:46:32.293
Because there's always the
penchant that probably my book

00:46:32.293 --> 00:46:33.900
might be adapted for a film.

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:35.460
VIKAS SWARUP: No, I never write
from that perspective.

00:46:35.460 --> 00:46:37.630
Because, look, if that is what
you're looking for, then write

00:46:37.630 --> 00:46:41.850
screenplays because that is the
correct medium for that.

00:46:41.850 --> 00:46:44.945
"Six Suspects," my second book,
when I was writing "Six

00:46:44.945 --> 00:46:47.930
Suspects," "Q &amp; A" was already
being made into a film.

00:46:47.930 --> 00:46:49.690
It had not been released
yet, but it was being

00:46:49.690 --> 00:46:50.640
made in to a film.

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:53.100
Yet I wrote "Six Suspects,"
which is a murder mystery.

00:46:53.100 --> 00:46:54.860
Now, you know, a who-done-it
is the most

00:46:54.860 --> 00:46:56.540
difficult book to film.

00:46:56.540 --> 00:46:58.270
In a book, how do you
disguise a murderer?

00:46:58.270 --> 00:47:00.980
Because I never had an idea
that this book would also

00:47:00.980 --> 00:47:03.150
become a film one day or
something like that.

00:47:03.150 --> 00:47:04.380
So when I write, I write.

00:47:04.380 --> 00:47:06.390
When I write a book,
I write a book.

00:47:06.390 --> 00:47:08.520
And I have no expectations
that this will

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:09.550
be made into a film.

00:47:09.550 --> 00:47:13.350
But many people tell me that I
write very visually in the

00:47:13.350 --> 00:47:16.440
sense that when I create my
book, then I am myself

00:47:16.440 --> 00:47:18.700
imagining that scene in my head,
and then I write from

00:47:18.700 --> 00:47:19.300
that perspective.

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:22.110
So that probably makes it easier
for it to be translated

00:47:22.110 --> 00:47:23.863
into another medium.

00:47:23.863 --> 00:47:25.795
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:47:25.795 --> 00:47:30.142
So how much say does a writer
ought to have when his work is

00:47:30.142 --> 00:47:34.060
being adapted into a movie?

00:47:34.060 --> 00:47:35.240
VIKAS SWARUP: That depends
on what kind of

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:36.180
contract you have.

00:47:36.180 --> 00:47:37.570
There is the British contract.

00:47:37.570 --> 00:47:40.800
There is the Hollywood
contract.

00:47:40.800 --> 00:47:43.530
The kind of contract
I had had me in

00:47:43.530 --> 00:47:45.030
charge of creative control.

00:47:45.030 --> 00:47:47.570
I had creative control in the
sense that I would have to

00:47:47.570 --> 00:47:48.720
sign off on the screenplay.

00:47:48.720 --> 00:47:51.000
So they would show me the
screenplay, accept my

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:54.030
suggestions if I had any, and
then on that basis proceed

00:47:54.030 --> 00:47:56.460
further, which I think is
the right way to go.

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:59.390
After all, no one is closer to
the work than the writer.

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:02.700
So any film people who want to
completely ignore the writer

00:48:02.700 --> 00:48:08.030
or cut out the writer from that
process I think is not

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:09.750
doing the right thing.

00:48:09.750 --> 00:48:13.730
Yes, there are some writers
who are so obsessive about

00:48:13.730 --> 00:48:16.650
their work that they can
become too interfering.

00:48:16.650 --> 00:48:20.800
I was on a panel with a Chinese
writer in Shanghai,

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:22.470
and he had a very interesting
take on

00:48:22.470 --> 00:48:23.480
this adaptation business.

00:48:23.480 --> 00:48:26.680
He said, the best attitude you
can have towards an adaptation

00:48:26.680 --> 00:48:30.450
of your work is that of
a distant relative.

00:48:30.450 --> 00:48:33.540
And he says that's very
effective because if the film

00:48:33.540 --> 00:48:35.350
does well, you can always
claim the relative.

00:48:35.350 --> 00:48:36.410
Oh, he's my relative.

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:38.200
And if it doesn't do well,
you can say I had

00:48:38.200 --> 00:48:38.840
nothing to do with it.

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:41.230
[LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE]

00:48:44.576 --> 00:48:46.020
AUDIENCE: I have one.

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:48.180
VIKAS SWARUP: Yes.

00:48:48.180 --> 00:48:50.510
AUDIENCE: When you were
speaking, I was a little

00:48:50.510 --> 00:48:53.080
amazed with you have
a day job.

00:48:53.080 --> 00:48:55.550
And then you said you dedicate
weekends to your passion,

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:56.830
which is writing.

00:48:56.830 --> 00:48:57.317
VIKAS SWARUP: Yes.

00:48:57.317 --> 00:48:58.780
AUDIENCE: What happens
to the family?

00:48:58.780 --> 00:49:02.590
Because in the discussions we
have here a lot of times are

00:49:02.590 --> 00:49:05.123
around work/life balance and,
oh, I don't have the time to

00:49:05.123 --> 00:49:09.042
pursue my passion, which
may be [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:09.042 --> 00:49:10.850
How do you organize your time?

00:49:10.850 --> 00:49:12.630
VIKAS SWARUP: No, that's
very, very important.

00:49:12.630 --> 00:49:15.380
And I am incredibly lucky to
have such a supportive family

00:49:15.380 --> 00:49:16.820
who give me the space
on weekends.

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:20.170
Because if Monday to Friday I'm
working at the office and

00:49:20.170 --> 00:49:22.470
Saturday and Sunday I'm doing my
wife's grocery list and my

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:25.130
son's homework, then they'll be
no time to create at all.

00:49:25.130 --> 00:49:27.070
So it's not that I work
every weekend.

00:49:27.070 --> 00:49:29.910
There are some weekends where
I goof off or we go with the

00:49:29.910 --> 00:49:33.770
family to an outing or travel
or catch a movie or

00:49:33.770 --> 00:49:34.540
something like that.

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:37.780
But when the idea is fully
formed in my head and I have

00:49:37.780 --> 00:49:41.200
started writing, then my family
respects that OK, he

00:49:41.200 --> 00:49:42.950
has reached that particular
point where we

00:49:42.950 --> 00:49:44.640
need to give him space.

00:49:44.640 --> 00:49:46.820
Otherwise, he'll be
a cranky old man.

00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:51.110
And then they allow me that
space and allow me to work.

00:49:51.110 --> 00:49:53.290
And without that, I think
without having a supportive

00:49:53.290 --> 00:49:56.586
family, the creative process
just does not work.

00:49:56.586 --> 00:49:59.827
AUDIENCE: Also a passion
for your art

00:49:59.827 --> 00:50:01.690
because you want to pursue--

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:02.500
VIKAS SWARUP: So that's
what I'm saying.

00:50:02.500 --> 00:50:04.430
You have to have the passion,
because if you don't have the

00:50:04.430 --> 00:50:06.950
passion, the creative juices
just won't flow.

00:50:06.950 --> 00:50:11.850
But for the passion to be
translated into a product, you

00:50:11.850 --> 00:50:13.690
have to have that supportive
family environment, which

00:50:13.690 --> 00:50:18.704
allows that creative
process to unfold.

00:50:18.704 --> 00:50:22.480
AUDIENCE: So one of the themes
in "Q &amp; A" and as you spoke

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:26.055
about "The Accidental
Apprentice" is the process of

00:50:26.055 --> 00:50:30.065
evaluating someone or judging
someone based on-- it could be

00:50:30.065 --> 00:50:31.940
a quiz based on this memory
or it could be

00:50:31.940 --> 00:50:33.190
something totally different.

00:50:33.190 --> 00:50:36.855
So was there any instant that
you actually lived or has

00:50:36.855 --> 00:50:39.140
there been a real-life
experience where you've seen

00:50:39.140 --> 00:50:40.944
people being evaluated
in a certain way?

00:50:40.944 --> 00:50:44.602
I mean, nowadays with access to
all the information, it may

00:50:44.602 --> 00:50:46.718
not be that someone has
everything in your mind.

00:50:46.718 --> 00:50:49.646
You have to know what to make
of it and how to get that.

00:50:49.646 --> 00:50:52.590
So do you have any anecdotal
stories of that?

00:50:52.590 --> 00:50:55.340
VIKAS SWARUP: This evaluation
that you're saying, it does

00:50:55.340 --> 00:50:57.350
not just happen in
the workplace.

00:50:57.350 --> 00:50:59.430
We evaluate people
all the time.

00:50:59.430 --> 00:51:02.620
In fact, the whole motivation
behind writing "Q &amp; A" was we

00:51:02.620 --> 00:51:05.630
have this tendency, especially
in India, that those of us who

00:51:05.630 --> 00:51:08.920
have the good fortune of getting
a decent education,

00:51:08.920 --> 00:51:12.260
going to school, universities,
reading newspapers, we believe

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:13.470
we know everything.

00:51:13.470 --> 00:51:16.590
And those who have not had this
good fortune, people who

00:51:16.590 --> 00:51:19.540
work for us, for instance, who
have not gone through a formal

00:51:19.540 --> 00:51:22.270
education system, we feel they
don't know anything.

00:51:22.270 --> 00:51:23.950
And we tend to put them down.

00:51:23.950 --> 00:51:24.750
You know, [SPEAKING HINDI].

00:51:24.750 --> 00:51:25.930
You don't know anything.

00:51:25.930 --> 00:51:27.960
And I have always been
tremendously impressed by the

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:30.930
amount of wisdom and knowledge
that these common folk possess

00:51:30.930 --> 00:51:32.770
who we don't give
the time of day.

00:51:32.770 --> 00:51:36.180
So the whole purpose behind
writing "Q &amp; A" was to show

00:51:36.180 --> 00:51:39.850
that the best teacher in the
world is life itself.

00:51:39.850 --> 00:51:42.940
And those who graduate from the
School of Hard Knocks know

00:51:42.940 --> 00:51:47.320
that every moment in life is
meaningful and precious and

00:51:47.320 --> 00:51:47.715
significant.

00:51:47.715 --> 00:51:50.120
There are no unnecessary
experiences.

00:51:50.120 --> 00:51:52.430
And that's what happens
in the book.

00:51:52.430 --> 00:51:55.610
Ram Mohammed Thomas has street
knowledge as opposed to book

00:51:55.610 --> 00:51:58.100
knowledge, and it is that street
knowledge that enables

00:51:58.100 --> 00:52:03.600
him to unlock the keys to the
questions not only onto the

00:52:03.600 --> 00:52:06.240
quiz show but to life itself.

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:09.870
AUDIENCE: Do you think that
art is just [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:09.870 --> 00:52:14.443
for art's sake, or should it
have a greater purpose and be

00:52:14.443 --> 00:52:15.590
socially responsible?

00:52:15.590 --> 00:52:18.230
VIKAS SWARUP: Well, that again
depends from writer to writer.

00:52:18.230 --> 00:52:19.440
There are some writers
who only seek

00:52:19.440 --> 00:52:20.810
to amuse and entertain.

00:52:20.810 --> 00:52:22.670
And there are some writers who
want to bring about social

00:52:22.670 --> 00:52:24.480
change and change the world.

00:52:24.480 --> 00:52:27.180
So both kinds of writers
I think have a

00:52:27.180 --> 00:52:28.120
place in the world.

00:52:28.120 --> 00:52:30.490
And I think both kinds of
stories can lead to the

00:52:30.490 --> 00:52:32.390
discovery of truth.

00:52:32.390 --> 00:52:35.650
The important thing is that
it's a personal truth.

00:52:35.650 --> 00:52:38.290
It is truth as seen or perceived
by the writer.

00:52:38.290 --> 00:52:41.320
Because remember, a novel is not
a reproduction of reality.

00:52:41.320 --> 00:52:42.750
It is a recreation.

00:52:42.750 --> 00:52:45.530
And when you recreate that
reality, you do so through the

00:52:45.530 --> 00:52:48.350
prism of your own experiences.

00:52:48.350 --> 00:52:52.250
So, as I said, the kind of books
I write, I do not set

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:54.880
out to be a game changer
or whatever.

00:52:54.880 --> 00:52:58.170
But at the same time, I say my
books may not have a message,

00:52:58.170 --> 00:52:59.880
but they have a conscience.

00:52:59.880 --> 00:53:03.060
That after you have read the
book, some issues if they are

00:53:03.060 --> 00:53:05.610
still lingering in your mind
about some of the issues that

00:53:05.610 --> 00:53:08.560
I have highlighted or touched
upon in my books, then I find

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:09.560
that to be a bonus.

00:53:09.560 --> 00:53:13.420
But primarily, I want you to get
engrossed in my book and

00:53:13.420 --> 00:53:14.670
enjoy the ride.

